From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Edmonton Sun, Thurs, 20 Jul 2000 [edited

Hand, foot and mouth outbreak - Edmonton (Alberta)
--------------------------------------------------
Warm weather and wading pools may be responsible for an outbreak of hand,
foot and mouth disease in kids, says the health watchdog for the Capital
Health Authority. Doctors around the region have been reporting an increase
in hand, foot and mouth cases since the end of June, said Dr. Gerry Predy,
chief Medical officer of Health. "They are seeing five or 6 people a day,"
he said. "It's definitely an outbreak." Kids are most vulnerable and most of
the cases have been children under age [?. Although the disease usually
has cyclical outbreaks every three or four years, one of the causes this
time around could be an epidemic of summer fun in backyard pools, he said.
"Wading pools - all the kids come in there and splash around," he said. "In
summertime people tend to be less careful washing their hands." Swimming
pools properly chlorinated don't pose a risk. The disease is spread through
direct contact with nose and throat discharges. People who catch it get
fever, sores in the mouth and a rash with blisters on the hands and feet.
Children will recover within 10 days. If the child also has a headache and
stiff neck there's a risk they may also have viral meningitis, he added.
(Byline Ian Mcdougall)
