[2
Date: Fri, 21 Jul 2000 00:27:58 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Toronto Star, 20 Jul 2000 04:46 EDT [edited

Hand, foot mouth disease - Toronto (Ontario)
--------------------------------------------
Officially, there isn't an epidemic of hand, foot and mouth disease among
children in Toronto. It's a claim Dr. Allison McGeer, Director of
Infectious Diseases at Mount Sinai Hospital, can neither verify nor dispute
because public health officials don't monitor its incidence. Hand, foot and
mouth disease is a childhood illness identifiable by sores on the cheeks,
gums, tongue, hands and feet - hence the name.
However, parents and child-care providers say an outbreak is sweeping
child-care centres in Toronto. But veteran day-care worker Penny Smith
trusts her 20 years of experience. The co-director of Sprouts Daycare said
she's never seen so many children infected. "Some cases are so mild, you
don't notice it," Smith said. "But in severe cases, children have sores in
the mouth, which makes them crabby, so we tell parents to keep their
children at home."
Two viruses - Coxsackie A16 and Enterovirus 71 - usually cause the disease.
It's transmitted by sneezing and coughing and by direct contact with nose
and throat secretions or the feces of infected people. McGeer said the
disease peaks in the summer and early fall, and like measles, which is more
prevalent every six or seven years, runs in multi-year cycles. Sores in the
mouth and on the feet can make it painful to eat or walk. McGeer said a
child can be infected and not show any symptoms. In that case, she says a
child can be contagious for weeks, thus rendering precautions ineffective.
All parents and caretakers can do, McGeer said, is to be a little more
vigilant about hand-washing and cleaning items like toys that may have been
in a child's mouth.

[Byline; Alison Blackduck
