[The virus responsible for these outbreaks in Edmonton and Toronto does not
appear to have been identified. The disease appears to be reasonably benign
in contrast to the current outbreak in Japan. Hand, foot and mouth disease
in children is something of an enigma; the same constellation of signs and
symptoms appearing in associated with infection by two quite distinct
picornaviruses. Meningitis is rare, but more commonly associated with
Enterovirus 71 infection. It is not a notifiable disease and has attracted
very little critical attention
Dr. Rick Lehtinen <lehtinenfamily@home.com> has made the following
interesting comments in response to my previous observations regarding the
epidemic in Japan. He writes "What caught my eye was the statement that the
periodicity of the outbreak in Japan seems (within the limited sample set of
three outbreaks 1990, 1995, 2000) to be five years, whereas in Europe it is
"three-four" years. The posting mentioned that severity was not apparently
associated with genotype, yet went on to state that Enterovirus-71 might be
the cause of the severity of the Asian outbreak. If we factor out genotype,
we are left with a possible association of severity and periodicity, in this
case, longer intervals with greater severity. Are there any data to support
(1) these apparent 5 and "3-4" year periods? (2)Any theories underlying this
apparent periodicity?
It would be interesting if anyone can produce hard data relevant to Dr.
Lehtinen's questions. I doubt, however, that there is a real difference in
periodicity. "Three-four" year intervals are clinician speak for "irregular
(i.e. not annual)" intervals. - Mod.CP
